      <p>(Sinicrope, Mick & Kolb, 2002)</p>
      <p>The follow example further expands on the last strategy in the table above, “Inverse of multiplication.” Since division is the inverse of multiplication, and a Cartesian product is calculated in a model for fraction multiplication (as in the area model described above), it makes sense that the inverse of a Cartesian product is calculated in a fraction division model. The following diagrams outline this inverse model:</p>
      <!-- PAGE 15/66 -->
      <q>Whole number division using the inverse of a Cartesian product model</q>
      <figure id="fig6"  class="center">
